The Cowell/Stevenson dining hall has always been a student favorite. From all-day pizza and fries, to their late night menus, itâ€™s easy to see why they're many people's first choice. Cowell also has a great location, overlooking the vast east field, as well as being situated a stone's throw away from the Athletic Center, which makes it common to see people come by for their post-workout meal.

Recently, however, this dining hall dominance may be coming to an end. This year weâ€™ve seen a trend where many other dining halls have started offering the same benefits that used to be exclusive to the top funded dining halls. These changes can be seen in every dining hall from Crown to Kresge, Crown has now started offering all day pizza and College 9 recently opened their second clean plate option allowing for twice the menu size with many more changes still in the works.

This recent competition between dining halls has been beneficial to both the student body and dining halls, which are more competitive than ever. The students have access to a much wider variety of quality food, while the dining halls benefit from getting more students through the door. As well as the culture shift, the new executive director for all dining services, Omar Galvez, has committed to improving equity between colleges. As we see more and more changes to the dining system, it can be assumed that many previously overlooked dining halls could become serious contenders for the next favorite spot.

The quality discrepancy between dining halls we currently see is undeniable, however, it does make one wonder how did this happen? Well, one large factor is how the dining halls are funded, which is done exclusively through meal plan revenue. This means, for the most part, dining halls are on their own for most of their funding, with improvements going to the most profitable dining halls. As a result, the dining halls with the most natural foot traffic get to reinvest in better equipment and a larger menu, furthering the quality gap between dining halls. This can be clearly seen in the Cowell dining hall, where they have a full brick oven for pizza, while other dining halls use a normal oven if they even offer pizza.

These changes will have drastic impacts on the future of dining at UCSC and it seems to be for the better. Dining halls are now becoming more equitable for all students in all colleges with new menu options and all-day improvements. The revitalized fierce competition between dining halls may force the current leading dining halls to further improve their dining experience. Overall, between the new director of dining services and the apparent culture shift inside the dining halls, it seems students are the biggest winner in this latest wave of changes with larger menus and better food.
